<h2>Heavy precipitation and windy conditions over Ireland and the UK</h2>
<br><br>
The crossing of a deep low-pressure system, originating from the tropical Atlantic, caused some exceptionally windy days with high precipitation and thunderstorms in Ireland, Scotland and England between 8 and 11 August. This led to flooding, traffic disruptions, fallen trees and landslides in Scotland and the northern parts of England. After the passage of this depression, the whole of Northwestern Europe enjoyed some warm days caused by a southerly flow related to a high-pressure area over the Eastern European mainland. This warm period occurred between 22 and 28 August, which was exceptionally late in the season. Several record high temperatures were registered.
<br><br>
Figure 1 shows the development of the deep depression over the Atlantic and crossing Ireland and the UK, and daily precipitation amounts. The warm period in the second half of the month is illustrated in Figure 2.
<br><br>
