<h2>Specific climate indicators for August 2019</h2>
<br><br>
<strong>Warm days in much of Europe, cold days in the east</strong>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG10p_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG10p_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg10p_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG90p_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG90p_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: Number of cold days (monthly mean temperature < 10th percentile, TG10p) and warm days (monthly mean temperature > 90th percentile, TG90p) in August 2019. Reference period for percentiles is 1961-1990.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Warm and cold days were very unevenly distributed within Europe in August (Fig. 3). A cold day is defined as a day when monthly mean temperature at a grid point was below the 10th percentile, which means among the 10% coldest August months (counted in the period 1961-1990); for a warm day monthly mean temperature was among the 10% warmest August months (>90th percentile of 1961-1990 period). In August 2019, much of Europe did not have any cold days or just very few except Eastern Europe, and especially Russia with up to 8 or 9 cold days. In terms of warm days, there were very few in Eastern Europe but also in westernmost parts of Europe, while especially in large parts of Southeastern Europe up to around 15 days were warm days.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_SU_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_SU_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_wsdi_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_WSDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_wsdi_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_WSDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_wsdi_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_wsdi_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 4: Number of summer days in August 2019 (daily maximum temperature at least 25&#176;C, SU) and Warm Spell Duration Index (number of days with daily maximum temperature >90th percentile (1961-1990 reference), WSDI). A warm spell is defined by at least 6 days duration.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Looking at fixed temperature thresholds instead of percentiles, there was a sharp border between Northern and Central/Southern Europe concerning the number of summer days (Fig. 4 left). Much of Central and Southern Europe still had summerly daily temperature maxima of at least 25&#176;C or more on at least 20 days in August 2019. In contrast, in Northern Europe this threshold was reached only in some places on a few days. One reason for this sharp distinction was a long warm spell, which occurred especially in parts of Central and Southeastern Europe in the last third of August 2019. The duration of this warm spell, caused by a persistent high pressure zone, was up to more than one week (Fig. 4 right).
<br><br>
<strong>Long dry periods in parts of Europe</strong>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_prcptot_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_PRCPTOT_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_prcptot_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_PRCPTOT_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_prcptot_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_prcptot_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_rr1_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_RR1_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_rr1_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_RR1_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_rr1_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_rr1_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2019/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2019_month_nc__2019-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 5: Monthly precipitation anomaly (PRCPTOT, deviation from 1981-2010 average), number of wet days (RR1, daily total at least 1 mm), and number of consecutive dry days (CDD, days with <1 mm precipitation) in August 2019. </em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Drought remained a great topic this August. There were two main zones of continuous dryness in Europe: one extending from France over Central Europe to the Baltic countries and Finland, the other one from the Balkans to Ukraine/Russia. The monthly precipitation deficit was locally above 40 mm (Fig. 5 left), which means that some places received less than 40% of the usual August total. Even more worrying for farmers and other water dependent economy sectors, however, was the long duration of periods without rain. Numbers of less than 10 rainy days (Fig. 5 middle), but 10 or more consecutive dry days (Fig. 5 right) were widespread in Europe, even in middle latitudes. Partly these periods were even much longer. In France, e.g. in Paris, no rain was measured during more than 30 days from 18 August 2019. Almost entire metropolitan France was concerned by water restrictions, parts of other countries as well.
<br><br>
<h2>The weather in August 2019</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
Most of Europe experienced average temperatures above the 1981-2010 average for August (Figure 7). Much above and exceptionally above normal temperatures, corresponding to the 75-90 and > 90 percentile ranges were recorded over large parts of central and eastern Europe and over the western part of Scandinavia (see Figure 8, middle panel). Regions with lower-than-normal temperatures in August were found in the far northeastern part of Europe and parts of Ireland and Portugal.
